PART II — COFFEE PIE® CIRCULAR ECONOMY ADDENDUM
===============================================================================

This Addendum governs the use of Coffee Pie® hardware designs (Codec Terminals
and associated modules and accessories: Commander™, Sentinel™, Ranger™ lines,
and any derivative or compatible hardware) under CERN-OHL-S v2, and sets
binding conditions specific to the Coffee Pie® ecosystem. In case of conflict
between Part I and Part II, Part II prevails for Coffee Pie® hardware.

The Coffee Pie® name, logo, QFDM™, Commander™, Sentinel™, Ranger™, and Patent
NC2025/0012723 are protected by trademark and patent law. CERN-OHL-S v2 does not
grant any rights over these marks or the patented QFDM system beyond what is
explicitly stated in this Addendum.


A. OPEN MANUFACTURING RIGHTS

   Anyone — individual, community, startup, or established manufacturer — may
   freely study, manufacture, modify, and distribute Codec Terminals, modules,
   and accessories covered by these designs, subject to the conditions of
   CERN-OHL-S v2 (Part I) and this Addendum (Part II).

   You are free to:
     - Build Codec Terminals for personal, educational, or research use at no
       royalty cost, with no obligation to connect to the QFDM Backend.
     - Propose, develop, and monetize your own compatible modules, accessories,
       peripherals, expansion cards, display devices, batteries, switches, and
       software around the Coffee Pie® service free of charge.
     - Sell or distribute compatible devices through your own channels, provided
       you comply with Section C (Circular Economy Obligations).

   You are NOT free to:
     - Connect Codec Terminals to the QFDM Backend for commercial rental to
       third parties without paying the applicable QFDM Royalty Fees (see Section B).
     - Use the Coffee Pie®, QFDM™, Commander™, Sentinel™, or Ranger™ trademarks
       or branding on your products without a separate brand license agreement.
     - Apply planned obsolescence or any design practice that intentionally
       shortens the useful life of a device.


B. QFDM BACKEND CONNECTION — QFDM ROYALTY FEES

   Connecting a Codec Terminal to the Coffee Pie® QFDM Backend for the purpose
   of renting or providing computing services to third parties (commercial use)
   requires payment of QFDM Royalty Fees to Grupo 3P1 Colombia (or an authorized
   royalty-collection agent) for use of the patented QFDM system (Patent
   NC2025/0012723). These are patent royalties, not a software license fee. The
   royalty schedule is as follows:

     Terminals connected to QFDM Backend (per unit/month):
       1     to    999 terminals:  1.00 USD/month per terminal
       1'000 to  9'999 terminals:  0.90 USD/month per terminal
       10'000 to 99'999 terminals: 0.70 USD/month per terminal
       100'000 to 999'999 terminals: 0.50 USD/month per terminal
       1'000'000+ terminals:       0.30 USD/month per terminal

   QFDM Royalty Fees are arranged at: https://www.coffeepie.co/panel (QFDM Royalty Fees Tab)

   Personal, educational, and research use connecting to the QFDM Backend (up to
   nine (9) terminals) is permitted free of charge under the Community License
   tier, subject to the conditions of the root repository LICENSE file.


C. CIRCULAR ECONOMY OBLIGATIONS

   The Coffee Pie® hardware ecosystem is founded on the principle that not a
   single gram of raw material should be wasted. Every device must return to
   the production lines at the end of its life cycle. By manufacturing,
   distributing, or renting any Product under this Licence, You irrevocably
   commit to ALL of the following:

   C.1  DESIGN FOR DURABILITY AND REPAIRABILITY
        Devices must achieve a repairability score of 9/10 or higher under the
        methodology defined at https://www.ifixit.com/repairability. This
        requires: modular construction, standardized fasteners, publicly
        available schematics and spare parts, no deliberate software locks that
        prevent repair, and a minimum structural lifespan of ten (10) years
        under normal use conditions.

   C.2  SPARE PARTS AVAILABILITY
        You must guarantee the availability of spare parts and replacement
        modules for every Product You Convey, for a minimum of ten (10) years
        from the date of last manufacture of that Product model.

   C.3  END-OF-LIFE COMMITMENT
        You must accept the return of any Product You have placed in service,
        at no cost to the end user or operator, at the end of its life cycle.
        Returned Products must be directed exclusively to:
          a) remanufacturing (restoration to original or improved specification);
          b) component harvesting for reuse in new Products; or
          c) certified material recycling — with documented proof of chain of
             custody and zero landfill disposal.

        Under no circumstances may a returned Product, or any of its components,
        be directed to incineration or landfill while recyclable material value
        remains.

   C.4  SERVICE PROVIDER OBLIGATION
        Manufacturers who rent Codec Terminals through the Coffee Pie® ecosystem
        (directly or via ISP partnerships) must repurchase their devices or contract, either directly or through authorized third parties, preventive maintenance, corrective maintenance, repair, restoration, remanufacturing, recycling, and/or final disposal services from:
          a) Grupo 3P1 Colombia (Coffee Pie®); or
          b) an authorized Coffee Pie® service partner listed at
             https://www.coffeepie.co/dispositivos-certificados.

        This obligation ensures that every device remains in productive service
        for as long as physically possible and that its raw materials return to
        the production cycle upon end of life.

   C.5  MATERIAL TRACEABILITY
        Manufacturers must maintain records identifying the primary materials
        used in each Product model (PCB substrate, metals, plastics, display
        panels, battery chemistry) and make these records available to any
        authorized recycler or end-of-life service provider upon request.

   C.6  NO PLANNED OBSOLESCENCE
        Any design practice, firmware update, software lock, or commercial
        strategy that intentionally shortens the useful life of a Product,
        artificially renders it incompatible with repairs or spare parts, or
        forces replacement before the end of its physical lifespan is strictly
        prohibited and constitutes a material breach of this Licence.


D. CERTIFICATION AND BRAND USE

   If You wish to manufacture Codec Terminals and sell or rent them under the
   Coffee Pie® brand (or as certified Coffee Pie®-compatible devices), You must:

     1. Submit Your design for review and certification at:
        https://www.coffeepie.co/fabricantes

     2. Demonstrate compliance with all conditions in Section C.

     3. Execute a separate Brand License Agreement with Grupo 3P1 Colombia.

   OEM/White-Label manufacturing (under your own brand) requires a QFDM Backend
   License (Section B) but does not require a Brand License Agreement, provided
   you clearly disclose Coffee Pie® compatibility in your product documentation.


E. COMMUNITY INCENTIVE PROGRAM

   Manufacturers with devices actively in service within the Coffee Pie®
   ecosystem are eligible for a monthly credit incentive of 1% of the rented
   asset value per active device, distributed as non-refundable platform credits.
   Credits are calculated on devices confirmed in active service and may be used
   to consume Coffee Pie® computing services or to promote products to the
   Coffee Pie® user base through the platform API/MCP.

   Devices confirmed as damaged, returned, or out of service in a given month
   are excluded from that month's incentive calculation.


F. TERMINATION

   In addition to the termination conditions in CERN-OHL-S v2 Section 8.4 and
   8.5, this Addendum and the QFDM Backend connection rights shall terminate
   immediately upon:
     - Any violation of the Circular Economy Obligations in Section C;
     - Connection of Codec Terminals to the QFDM Backend without payment of the
       applicable QFDM Royalty Fees;
     - Use of Coffee Pie® trademarks without authorization;
     - Any confirmed instance of planned obsolescence as defined in Section C.6.


G. GOVERNING PHILOSOPHY

   "We came to life empty-handed, we will leave life empty-handed."

   The Coffee Pie® hardware ecosystem exists to prove that high technology and
   environmental responsibility are not in conflict — that it is possible to
   eradicate electronic waste, extend the productive life of every gram of raw
   material extracted from the Earth, and still build a thriving, profitable,
   and equitable ecosystem for manufacturers, users, and the communities they
   serve.

   This is not an aspiration. It is a binding condition of participation.


H. NORMATIVE REFERENCES

   The terms and obligations in this Licence, particularly in Part II Section C
   (Circular Economy Obligations), are interpreted in accordance with the
   following internationally recognized standards and directives. Compliance with
   these standards is strongly recommended and, where cited in Section C,
   constitutes part of the binding obligations of this Licence.

   H.1  ISO 14040:2006 — Environmental Management: Life Cycle Assessment —
        Principles and Framework.
        Defines the methodology and vocabulary for Life Cycle Assessment (LCA),
        including the term 'life cycle' as used throughout this Addendum.
        https://www.iso.org/standard/37456.html

   H.2  ISO 14044:2006 — Environmental Management: Life Cycle Assessment —
        Requirements and Guidelines.
        Specifies requirements and provides guidelines for LCA, including goal
        definition, inventory analysis, impact assessment, and interpretation.
        https://www.iso.org/standard/38498.html

   H.3  ISO 14001:2015 — Environmental Management Systems — Requirements with
        Guidance for Use.
        Provides the framework for an effective environmental management system
        that manufacturers operating under this Licence are encouraged to adopt.
        https://www.iso.org/standard/60857.html

   H.4  IEC 62635:2012 — Guidelines for End-of-Life Information on
        Electrotechnical Products and for End-of-Life Assessment of
        Electrotechnical Products.
        Establishes guidelines for the disclosure of end-of-life information and
        for the assessment of end-of-life treatment of electrotechnical products,
        directly informing Section C.3 (End-of-Life Commitment) and C.5
        (Material Traceability).
        https://www.iec.ch/standards/iec-62635

   H.5  EN 45554:2020 — General Methods for the Assessment of the Ability to
        Repair, Reuse and Upgrade Energy-Related Products.
        Defines the repairability scoring methodology referenced in Section C.1
        (Design for Durability and Repairability). The 9/10 repairability score
        threshold is interpreted under this standard and the iFixit Repairability
        Score methodology (https://www.ifixit.com/repairability).

   H.6  EU Directive 2011/65/EU (RoHS) — Restriction of the Use of Certain
        Hazardous Substances in Electrical and Electronic Equipment, and its
        amendment EU 2015/863.
        All Products manufactured under this Licence must comply with RoHS
        restrictions on hazardous substances. This is a minimum baseline; more
        stringent material restrictions may apply under national law.
        https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX:32011L0065

   H.7  EU Directive 2012/19/EU (WEEE) — Waste Electrical and Electronic
        Equipment.
        Establishes producer responsibility for the collection, treatment,
        recovery, and environmentally sound disposal of electrical and electronic
        equipment. Section C.3 (End-of-Life Commitment) and C.4 (Service
        Provider Obligation) are designed to meet and exceed the minimum
        requirements of this Directive.
        https://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=CELEX:32012L0019

   H.8  EU Circular Economy Action Plan (2020) — A New Circular Economy Action
        Plan for a Cleaner and More Competitive Europe.
        The policy framework that informed the design of this Addendum as a
        whole. The Coffee Pie® ecosystem is designed to be a practical
        implementation of circular economy principles as defined therein.
        https://environment.ec.europa.eu/strategy/circular-economy-action-plan_en


